{"cursor":"9325","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\n'Defence' ('defense' in the United States) in ice hockey is a player position\nwhose primary responsibility is to prevent the opposing team from scoring. They\nare often referred to as 'defencemen', 'defensemen', 'D', 'D-men' or\n\"blueliners\" (the latter a reference to the blue line in ice hockey which\nrepresents the boundary of the offensive zone; defencemen generally position\nthemselves along the line to keep the puck in the zone). They were once called\ncover-point.\n\nIn regular play, two defencemen complement three forwards and a goaltender on\nthe ice. Exceptions include overtime during the regular season and when a team\nis shorthanded (i.e. has been assessed a penalty), in which two defencemen are\ntypically joined by only two forwards and a goaltender.\n","linknr":187,"url":"Defenceman_(ice_hockey)","recorded":1362546686,"links":23,"instances":["ice_hockey","ice_hockey","ice_hockey","ice_hockey","ice_hockey","sport","hockey","ice_hockey","ice_hockey","ice_hockey","ice_hockey"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Ice hockey positions","Ice hockey strategy"],"headings":["Distinguished defencemen","'Stay-at-home' and 'offensive defence'","Faceoffs","Skating","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/30px-Commons-logo.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/HockeyRink.png/100px-HockeyRink.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["goal","ice_hockey"],["forward","ice_hockey"],["overtime","ice_hockey"],["shorthanded","ice_hockey"],["offside","ice_hockey"],["slot","ice_hockey"],["breakaway","ice_hockey"],["offsi